<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-06">
  <title>Week 6</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-fund-thm-of-top">
      <title>The fundamental theorem of topology</title>
      <p>
        The fundamental theorem of calculus allows us to compute definite integrals by evaluation of antiderivatives. The 
        fundamental theorem of arithmetic asserts that integers have unique prime factorizations. The fundamental theorem of linear 
        algebra should be the rank-nullity theorem but few are brave enough to say so. 
        The fundamental theorem of algebra guarantees that nonconstant complex polynomials have a root (and thus 
        <m>\mathbb C</m> is algebraically closed). 
      </p>
      <exercise>
        <title>Fundamental theorems</title>
        <p>
          What theorems in other domains do you think deserve to be called <term>fundamental</term>?
        </p>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        The fundamental theorem of topology — <ie />, point-set topology — provides convenient conditions under which 
        bijective continuous maps are homeomorphisms. We have already studied how such maps can fail to be homeomorphisms 
        — remember <m>[0,1)\to S^1,~t\mapsto e^{2\pi i t}</m> and the identity map from the discrete to concrete topology — 
        and we have experienced challenges producing explicit continuous inverse functions even when a continuous bijection 
        is a homeomorphism. The fundamental theorem will at least partially rectify this situation, providing a rich class of 
        (co)domains for which continuous bijections are necessarily homeomorphisms.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-FTT">
        <title>Fundamental theorem of topology</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>X</m> is a compact space and <m>Y</m> separates points. Then any continuous bijection <m>X\to Y</m> is a 
            homeomorphism.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          It suffices to prove that <m>f</m> is a closed map, <ie />, that for all <m>C\subseteq X</m> closed, <m>fC\subseteq Y</m> is closed. Since 
          <m>X</m> is compact, each closed subspace <m>C</m> of <m>X</m> is compact. And since the continuous image of a compact set is compact, 
          <m>fC\subseteq Y</m> is compact. Finally, compact subspaces of spaces that separate points are necessarily closed, so <m>fC\subseteq Y</m> is 
          closed for all <m>C\subseteq X</m> closed. This demonstrates that <m>f</m> is a homeomorphism.
        </p>
      </proof>
      
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-hausdorff-quotient">
    <title>When do quotients separate points?</title>
    <p>
      To close out our study of compactness, we develop a condition under which quotient topologies separate points. As you saw in the homework, 
      the line with two origins does not separate points despite being the quotient of a Hausdorff space. 
    </p>
    <p>
      We need a prepatory lemma, though:
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-projection-closed-map">
  <title>Projection from a product with a compact factor is a closed map</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces with <m>Y</m> compact. Then the projection
      <m>\operatorname{pr}_1 \colon X \times Y \to X</m> is a closed map.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Let <m>C \subseteq X \times Y</m> be closed; we must show that
      <m>\operatorname{pr}_1(C)</m> is closed in <m>X</m>. Equivalently, we show that
      <m>X \smallsetminus \operatorname{pr}_1(C)</m> is open, i.e. that every point
      <m>x_0 \in X \smallsetminus \operatorname{pr}_1(C)</m> has an open neighborhood
      disjoint from <m>\operatorname{pr}_1(C)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Fix such an <m>x_0</m>. The condition <m>x_0 \notin \operatorname{pr}_1(C)</m> means
      that <m>\{x_0\} \times Y</m> and <m>C</m> are disjoint. Since <m>C</m> is closed,
      its complement <m>(X \times Y) \smallsetminus C</m> is an open set that contains
      <m>\{x_0\} \times Y</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For each <m>y \in Y</m>, the point <m>(x_0, y)</m> lies in the open set
      <m>(X \times Y) \smallsetminus C</m>, so by the definition of the product topology
      there exist open sets <m>U_y \subseteq X</m> and <m>V_y \subseteq Y</m> such that
      <md>
        (x_0, y) \in U_y \times V_y \subseteq (X \times Y) \smallsetminus C.
      </md>
      The collection <m>\{V_y\}_{y \in Y}</m> is an open cover of <m>Y</m>. Since
      <m>Y</m> is compact, there is a finite subcover
      <m>V_{y_1}, \ldots, V_{y_n}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Set <m>U = U_{y_1} \cap \cdots \cap U_{y_n}</m>, which is a finite intersection of
      open sets containing <m>x_0</m>, hence an open neighborhood of <m>x_0</m> in
      <m>X</m>. We claim that <m>U \times Y \subseteq (X \times Y) \smallsetminus C</m>,
      which will imply <m>U \cap \operatorname{pr}_1(C) = \varnothing</m> and complete
      the proof.
    </p>
    <p>
      Indeed, let <m>(x, y) \in U \times Y</m> be arbitrary. Since
      <m>V_{y_1}, \ldots, V_{y_n}</m> cover <m>Y</m>, we have <m>y \in V_{y_k}</m> for
      some <m>k</m>. Since <m>x \in U \subseteq U_{y_k}</m>, it follows that
      <m>(x, y) \in U_{y_k} \times V_{y_k} \subseteq (X \times Y) \smallsetminus C</m>.
      Hence <m>(x,y) \notin C</m>, as desired.
    </p>
  </proof>
</lemma>
    <p>
      OK, on to our final theorem about Hausdorff quotients:
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-hausdorff-quotient">
      <title>Quotients that separate points</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> is a quotient map and define
          <md>
            E_q := \{(x,y)\in X\times X\mid q(x)=q(y)\}.
          </md>
          <aside>
            <title>Additional hypothesis!</title>
            <p>
              Note the additional hypothesis — that <m>X</m> is compact — in the converse theorem. Find an example demonstrating that 
              this additional hypothesis is necessary.
            </p>
          </aside>
          If <m>Z</m> separates points, then <m>E_q</m> is a closed subset of <m>X\times X</m>. If <m>X</m> is compact and 
          <m>E_q\subseteq X\times X</m> is closed, then <m>Z</m> separates points.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <example>
      <p>
      In the case of the line with two origins — realized as a quotient of <m>\mathbb R_1\amalg \mathbb R_2</m> — the set 
      <m>E_q</m> can be viewed as a subspace of the four disjoint planes <m>\mathbb R_i\times\mathbb R_j</m>, <m>i,j=1,2</m>. 
      Within <m>\mathbb R_1\times R_2</m>, <m>E_q</m> consists of the punctured diagonal consisting of <m>(x,x)\in \mathbb R^2</m> 
      with <m>x\ne 0</m>. This set is not closed, whence <m>E_q</m> is not closed, and thus the line with two origins is not 
      Hausdorff.
      </p>
    </example>
    <proof>
      <title>Proof of <xref ref="thm-hausdorff-quotient" /></title>
      <p>
        The statement is vacuously true when <m>Z</m> has zero or one elements. Assume henceforth that <m>Z</m> has at least two 
        distinct elements.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the forwards direction, assume that <m>Z</m> separates points. We need to show that <m>E_q</m> is closed. To this end, 
        consider <m>(x,y)\in (X\times X)\smallsetminus E_q</m>. Then <m>q(x)\ne q(y)</m>. Since <m>Z</m> separates points, we may 
        choose <m>V_x,V_y\subseteq Z</m> disjoint open neighborhoods of <m>x,y</m>, respectively. Since <m>q</m> is continuous and 
        <m>X\times X</m> has the product topology, <m>q^{-1}V_x\times q^{-1}V_y</m> is an open neighborhood of <m>(x,y)</m> in 
        <m>X\times X</m>. We now show that
        <md>
          E_q\cap (q^{-1}V_x\times q^{-1}V_y) = \varnothing.
        </md>
        Indeed, if <m>(x',y')</m> is in the intersection, then <m>q(x')=q(y')</m>, contradicting the disjointness of <m>V_x,V_y</m>. We 
        have now demonstrated that every <m>(x,y)\in (X\times X)\smallsetminus E_q</m> has an open neighborhood that is a subset of 
        <m>(X\times X)\smallsetminus E_q</m>, whence <m>E_q</m> is closed, as desired.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the backwards direction, assume <m>X</m> is compact and <m>E_q\subseteq X\times X</m> is closed. I will sketch an argument 
        for why this implies that the diagonal subspace <m>\{(z,z)\mid z\in Z\}\subseteq Z\times Z</m> is closed. In your homework, 
        you proved that this is equivalent to separating points.
      </p>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Step 1</title>
          <p>
            Show that <m>q</m> is a closed map. (You will need to use the hypothesis that <m>E_q</m> is closed. It might be helpful to 
            write <m>q^{-1}qC = \operatorname{pr_1}(E_q\cap (X\times C)</m> and to employ the above lemma.)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Step 2</title>
          <p>
            Show that <m>q\times q\colon X\times X\to Z\times Z</m> is a closed surjection, and then recall (or prove) that closed 
            surjections are quotient maps.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Step 3</title>
          <p>
            Since <m>q\times q</m> is a quotient map, a subset of <m>Z\times Z</m> is closed if and only if its preimage under 
            <m>q\times q</m> is closed. The preimage of the diagonal subspace of <m>Z\times Z</m> under <m>q</m> is exactly 
            <m>E_q</m>, which is closed by hypothesis.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </proof>
    <example>
      <title>Quotients that separate points</title>
      <p>
        Here is a brief list of quotient constructions that separate points according to the above theorem. You should identify 
        <m>E_q</m> and verify that it is closed.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              For <m>A\subseteq X</m>, define <m>X/A</m> to be the quotient 
              of <m>X</m> by the equivalence relation generated by <m>a\sim b</m> for all <m>a,b\in A</m>. We say that <m>X/A</m> 
              <term>collapses</term> <m>A</m> to a point. Suppose <m>X</m> is compact and separates points and that <m>A\subseteq X</m> is closed. 
              Then <m>X/A</m> separates points. It follows that <m>S^n\cong D^n/\partial D^n</m> separates points, as does the cone on any compact 
              point-separating space.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Real projective space <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> can be realized as the quotient of <m>S^n</m> that identifies antipodal points. Since 
              <m>S^n</m> is compact and separates points and <m>E_q = \{(x,\pm x)\mid x\in S^n\}</m> is closed — check this! —, we learn that 
              <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> separates points.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>
    </subsubsection> 
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-connectedness">
      <title>Connectedness</title>
      <p>
        We now begin an exploration of a deep and important topological invariant: connectedness. You probably have an intuitive grasp 
        of this concept already. The real line <m>\mathbb R</m> has "one piece" — <ie />, is connected — while the punctured line 
        <m>\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}</m> has "two pieces" — it is disconnected.
      </p>
      <p>
        You have used connectivity before, though its fundamental role was probably cloaked in secrecy. For instance, the intermediate value theorem guarantees that, for a continuous 
        function <m>f\colon \mathbb R\to \mathbb R</m>, if there exists real numbers <m>a\lt b</m> for which <m>f(a)\lt 0</m> and 
        <m>f(b)\gt 0</m>, then there exists <m>a\lt x\lt b</m> for which <m>f(x)=0</m>. As we shall see, this is a consequence of <m>\mathbb R</m> being 
        connected. Meanwhile, consider the continuous function <m>g\colon \mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}\to \mathbb R</m> given by <m>g(t)=1/t</m>. 
        Despite <m>g(\pm 1)=\pm 1</m>, there is no <m>-1\lt x\lt 1</m> in <m>\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}</m> for which <m>g(x)=0</m>. This is only possible 
        because <m>\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}</m> is not connected.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-separation">
        <title>Separation of a space</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>separation</term> of a space <m>X</m> is a partition of <m>X</m> by nonempty open subsets; that is, a pair of nonempty open sets 
            <m>U,V\subseteq X</m> for which <m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m> and <m>U\cup V=X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <exercise>
        <title>Separations as coproducts</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that a space <m>X</m> has a separation if and only if <m>X\cong U\amalg V</m> for some spaces <m>U,V</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>